{"id":"1405.5233","submitter":"Michael Mossinghoff","authors":"Kevin G. Hare and Michael J. Mossinghoff","title":"Most Reinhardt polygons are sporadic","comments":"18 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.MG math.CO math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A \\textit{Reinhardt polygon} is a convex $n$-gon that, for $n$ not a power of\n$2$, is optimal in three different geometric optimization problems, for\nexample, it has maximal perimeter relative to its diameter. Some such polygons\nexhibit a particular periodic structure; others are termed \\textit{sporadic}.\nPrior work has described the periodic case completely, and has shown that\nsporadic Reinhardt polygons occur for all $n$ of the form $n=pqr$ with $p$ and\n$q$ distinct odd primes and $r\\geq2$. We show that (dihedral equivalence\nclasses of) sporadic Reinhardt polygons outnumber the periodic ones for almost\nall $n$, and find that this first occurs at $n=105$. We also determine a\nformula for the number of sporadic Reinhardt polygons when $n=2pq$ with $p$ and\n$q$ distinct odd primes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 20 May 2014 20:25:44 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 25 Oct 2014 00:47:48 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-10-28"}
